[Event "The Scotch Gambit Starter Kit"]
[White "Welcome to the Scotch Gambit"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2022.11.08"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/19999439"]
[ECO "C44"]

{ Hey there, welcome to the Scotch Gambit Opening Prep course! Since I first began playing chess, one of my main motivations to improve was to get beautiful games that made me incredibly proud. Throughout my chess journey, the Scotch Gambit has allowed me to do just that. In my opinion, the Scotch Gambit has a unique ability to balance the aggressive play of a gambit, with the safer positional variations that give White everything they can ask for out of an opening. You'll learn multiple strange lines that fall under the radar of most players, so even if you are looking to counter the Scotch Gambit, you'll find these ideas quite useful. Before we start studying the variations, I'll share my very first Scotch Gambit game, which at the time got me my highest rated win. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Be5,Bd5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } Nf6 {[%cal Bf6e4][%csl Be4]} { Here, Black played an inferior variation, aiming for an exchange in the center. } 
4. dxe5 Nxe4 
5. Bc4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Bd1d5][%csl Bf7]} { Already, White is threatening to sacrifice on f7 . } Bc5 {[%cal Bc5f2,Be4f2][%csl Bf2]} { Black plays a natural looking move, developing the bishop and eyeing down the f2-square. } 
6. Qd5 { But unfortunately for Black, they miss the response Qd5 , targeting f7 and the e4-knight. } Bxf2+ {[%cal Bd5e4,Bd5f7][%csl Be4,Bf7]} 
7. Ke2 Qe7 
8. Qxe4 Bb6 {[%csl Bc3,Bc1,Bc4,Bf3]} { Not even ten moves in, White is already up a knight for a pawn. } 
9. Nc3 O-O 
10. Be3 Qb4 {[%cal Bb4b2][%csl Bb2]} 
11. Nd5 {[%cal Bd5b4][%csl Bb4]} { Black is aiming to recoup some of the lost material, but leaves the kingside completely unprotected. } Qxb2 { White is looking to play Bd3 and threaten checkmate, but the move g6 would keep Black in the game... } 
12. Nf6+ {[%cal Bf6h7,Be4h7][%csl Bh7]} { Nf6+ completely destroys Black's kingside, preventing Black from defending h7 with g6 . } gxf6 { Black is forced to capture, and Bd3 becomes an unstoppable threat. } 
13. Bd3 {[%cal Be4h7][%csl Bh7]} Re8 
14. Qxh7+ Kf8 
15. Qh6+ {[%cal Bh6f6][%csl Bf6]} { Black tries to run, but our e5-pawn is a thorn in Black's position. } Kg8 
16. Bh7+ Kh8 { Finally, using a little mating combination, we can end the game in style. } 
17. Bg6+ Kg8 
18. Qh7+ Kf8 
{ After studying these very lines, it felt incredible to see this game play out exactly as I had practiced. I've done my best to cover all the realistic responses that you may encounter in your games, so that you can have a similar experience. I hope this course helps you, and wish you the best of luck in all your games. } 19. Qxf7# *

