1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Be5,Bd5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } exd4 
4. Bc4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Be4e5][%csl Be5,Bf7]} { Many players are familiar with the continuation Nxd4 , the mainline of the Scotch. Instead, the Scotch Gambit continues with the move Bc4 , delaying the recapture of the d4 pawn. This applies pressure to the weak f7-square and keeps the knight on f3 , where it continues to support the pawn push e5 . } Nf6 
5. e5 {[%cal Be5f6][%csl Bf6]} ( { While we will usually focus on 5. e5, it's important to mention the popular alternative } 5.O-O { . The line continues with } 5...Nxe4 6.Re1 d5 7.Bxd5 Qxd5 { and now the tactical } 8.Nc3 { , putting pressure on the } { e4 knight. 8...Qh5 9.Nxe4 . } ) d5 
6. Bb5 {[%cal Bb5e8,Bf3d4,Bd1d4][%csl Bd4]} ( { The continuation } 6.exf6 dxc4 7.O-O gxf6 { gives black the center and a pawn. } ) { White continues applying central pressure by pinning the c6-Knight. } Ne4 
7. Nxd4 {[%cal Bd4c6,Bb5c6][%csl Bc6]} { Finally, White recaptures the d4 pawn and threatens to harm the structure of black's queenside. } Bd7 
8. Bxc6 { White captures on c6 to create a pawn weakness and take the pressure off of e5 . } bxc6 {[%csl Bc7,Bc6]} 
9. O-O ( { Although f2-f3-f4 is part of White's plan, we should avoid playing it until our king is castled since: } 9.f3 Qh4+ { . } ) Bc5 
10. Be3 {[%cal Bf2f3,Bf3e4,Bb1d2][%csl Be4,Bd2]} { At first, this variation may seem a bit chaotic, but that's the best part! As you explore all the possible alternatives in the future, you will realize that Black will have to find these exact ideas to avoid giving White an advantage. This means that a lot of games will be won in the opening against unprepared opponents. Here, White and Black are on even ground, but white is threatening an aggressive f2-f3-f4 advance with tempo on the knight. White's biggest weakness is the overextended pawn on e5 , which is often sacrificed in the later stages of the game to aid the kingside attack. } *

