6. Bb5 {[%cal Bb5e8,Bf3d4,Bd1d4][%csl Bd4]} Ne4 
7. Nxd4 {[%cal Bd4c6,Bb5c6][%csl Bc6]} Bc5 {[%cal Bc5f2][%csl Bf2]} 
8. Be3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { In the previous variation, we analyzed the simple Bd7 . Here, Black is inviting Nxc6 . However, if you capture with the intent of winning the rook, you will be disappointed: } 8.Nxc6 Bxf2 9.Kf1 bxc6 10.Bxc6+ Kf8 { and there is no time to capture the rook as } 11.Bxa8 Ba6+ { forces white to give up the queen. Instead we will play the most solid move } ) ( 8.Be3 { . } ) Bd7 
9. Bxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Bc7,Bc6]} 
10. O-O { Notice that we have transposed to the position presented in the previous variation. As always, avoid advancing f2-f3 until the king has castled to prevent the nasty Qh4+ . } Bb6 {[%cal Be4c5,Bf2f3][%csl Bc5,Bf3]} 
11. Nd2 ( { Black retreats the bishop to a safer post on b6 to avoid any discovered attacks in the future. This move also allows the e4-knight to retreat to the vacant c5-square and prevents White from playing } 11.f3 Ng5 12.f4 { with tempo. } ) Nxd2 
12. Qxd2 c5 {[%cal Bd5d4,Bc5c4][%csl Bc4,Bd4]} { Black won't allow the f2-f4-f5 advance without some counter play. Although we are just out of the opening, Black has their sights set on creating a passed d-pawn. } 
13. Ne2 d4 
14. Bg5 {[%cal Bf2f4,Bg5d8][%csl Bf4,Bd8]} Qc8 
15. f4 { White finally puts their plan in action. } h6 
16. Bh4 O-O 
17. Ng3 { White swings the knight to g3 to add support for the f5 advance. } c4 
18. Kh1 {[%cal Bf8e8,Bd7f5,Ba1e1][%csl Be8,Bf5,Be1]} ( { There are two paths from this position. White should be wary of the threats on the b6-g1 and b7-h1 diagonals pointing right towards the king, and can play the patient } 18.Kh1 { , or continue with the aggressive } ) ( 18.f5 c3 19.Qf4 cxb2 20.Rab1 Bb5 21.Rfe1 { where both players are playing an all or nothing game. } ) ( { White's goal is to win control over f5 and break through with the f4-f5-f6 advance. Black should continue with } 18. Bf5 to prevent the immediate advance. White should counter by bringing the a1-rook to e1 to support the e5 pawn. A possible continuation after18...Bf5 { is } { 19.Nxf5 Qxf5 20.h3 with the aggressive g4 plan. } ) *

