{ This is an example game from my first tournament after my return to chess: the 2021 USCF Junior Congress. At the time I was rated 1226 and my opponent was rated 2015; the time control was 60+5. As you'll see, I was only a single move from ending the day 3/3 against players rated 1900-2100. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Bd5,Be5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } exd4 
4. Bc4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Be4e5][%csl Be5,Bf7]} Nf6 
5. e5 {[%cal Be5f6][%csl Bf6]} d5 {[%cal Bd5c4][%csl Bc4]} 
6. Bb5 {[%cal Bb5e8,Bf3d4,Bd1d4][%csl Bd4]} Ne4 
7. Nxd4 {[%cal Bd4c6,Bb5c6][%csl Bc6]} { Now that the e5-pawn is safe, White finally recaptures in the center and applies pressure on the c6-knight. } Bc5 {[%cal Bc5f2][%csl Bf2]} { Black is inviting tactical lines following 8. Nxc6 , but White chooses the calmer 8. Be3 . } 
8. Be3 O-O 
9. Nxc6 bxc6 
10. Bxc5 {[%cal Bc5f8][%csl Bf8]} ( { White makes sure to capture the c5-bishop first, as } 10.Bxc6 Bxe3 11.fxe3 Qh4+ { is disastrous for White. } ) Nxc5 
11. Bxc6 {[%cal Bc6a8][%csl Ba8]} Rb8 {[%cal Bb8b2][%csl Bb2]} 
12. Qxd5 { Black has the option to exchange queens and win back the pawn on b2, but often chooses a more dynamic game. } Qe7 {[%cal Bf8d8,Bc8a6][%csl Bd8,Ba6]} 
13. O-O Ba6 
14. Re1 Rfd8 
15. Qf3 { Black was able to activate their material with tempo, but White stabilizes before Black can cause any damage. } Rxb2 
16. Nc3 {[%cal Bc3d5,Ba1d1][%csl Bd5,Bd1]} { White's knight is headed to d5 , and the a1-rook is headed to d1 , the position is quickly becoming tactical. } Ne6 { Black takes a move to regroup their pieces and stabilize the position. } 
17. Nd5 {[%cal Bd5e7,Bd5f6][%csl Be7,Bf6]} Qc5 
18. Rad1 Nd4 { Here Black blunders, since after 18...Nd4 19. Qe3 the knight is pinned against the queen and the discovered attack on the d-file. Unfortunately I missed this tactic and lost shortly after miscalculating the Nf6 sacrifice. } 
19. Qe3 {[%cal Be3c5,Bd1d8][%csl Bc5,Bd8]} { Although Black is the one to offer the pawn sacrifice in this variation, White is by no means playing a defensive game. } *

