1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Be5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } exd4 
4. Bc4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Be4e5][%csl Be5,Bf7]} Nf6 
5. e5 {[%cal Be5f6][%csl Bf6]} Ng4 { As it turns out, Ng4 is an incredibly interesting move. At first glance it appears natural and sound, then suddenly White finds the tactical sacrifice Bxf7... but after the dust settles, Black somehow walks away with a slight advantage. In this lesson, we will explore the strongest continuation for White, but I include a demonstration of the Bxf7+ sacrifice in a sample game later in this chapter. } 
6. Qe2 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Be2e8][%csl Be8]} { White adds pressure by playing Qe2 . This move does two things: We prevent Black from immediately recapturing and bringing the knight towards the center, and we prevent the d6-pawn break by threatening to capture with check. The next series of moves shows both players fighting for the e5-pawn. } Qe7 
7. Bg5 f6 
8. exf6 { White gives into the pressure and captures on f6 . } gxf6 
9. Bh4 Qxe2+ 
10. Bxe2 {[%cal Be1a1,Bb1d2,Bd2b3][%csl Bb3]} { Looking around... White has natural development and is prepared to fight along the d-file to target Black's weaknesses. } Bb4+ 
11. Nbd2 O-O 
12. O-O-O {[%cal Bh2h3,Bg2g4,Bd2b3,Bb3d4][%csl Bd4]} { Despite being a pawn down, White's plan to castle queenside and target Black's weak pawn structure is in full motion. White is ready to play Nb3 and start advancing on the kingside, using Black's pawns as hooks to open up lines against Black's king. } *

