{ This was the opening sequence of first game played at the 2020 National Online Scholastic Chess Championship. The time control was 25+5, most of which was was spent scratching my head trying to figure out where I slipped up. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Be5,Bd5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } exd4 
4. Bc4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Be4e5][%csl Be5,Bf7]} Nf6 
5. e5 {[%cal Be5f6][%csl Bf6]} Ng4 {[%cal Bc4f7,Bf3g5][%csl Bf7,Bg5]} { Black invites the Bxf7+ sacrifice. } 
6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 
7. Ng5+ Kg8 { Here, White shouldn't recapture the g4-knight, as 8. Qxg4 d5 gives black the center and a strong positional advantage. Instead White plays a more tactical move, nearly ending the game. } 
8. Qf3 {[%cal Bf3d5,Bf3f7,Bf3b3][%csl Bf7,Bd5,Bb3]} Bb4+ {[%cal Bf3d5,Bg8f8][%csl Bd5,Bf8]} { Black's saving grace, indirectly defending against mate on d5 by creating an escape square for the king. } 
9. c3 Ngxe5 
10. Qd5+ Kf8 
11. O-O {[%cal Bf2f4,Bd5f7,Bg5f7][%csl Bf4,Bf7]} { White delays recapturing, instead preparing to play f4 , threatening the defender of f7 , and lining up the rook on the f-file. } Qf6 
12. cxb4 { Here White finds their attack running out of fuse, and begins to feel the pressure of their own queenside weaknesses. Being down a pawn doesn't help either. } *

