1. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 {[%cal Bd4d5,Bd4e5][%csl Be5,Bd5]} { White strikes in the center immediately with d4 , threatening to capture e5 or advance to d5 if Black doesn't exchange. } d6 
4. d5 ( { White always has the simple } 4.dxe5 dxe5 5.Qxd8 { , and Black loses castling rights. However, trading queens this way and playing a symmetrical position gives up a lot of winning chances. } ) Nce7 
5. c4 {[%cal Bb1c3,Bf1d3,Bc4c5][%csl Bc3,Bd3,Bc5]} { White grabs all the space he can ask for, but Black's position will not be easy to break into. } f5 {[%cal Bg8f6,Bf5f4][%csl Bf6,Bf4]} { Black has no obligation to execute this f5 plan. You may commonly encounter the move b6 , significantly slowing White's queenside expansion and giving Black enough time to build a more passive fianchetto setup on the kingside. In that case, White should still continue queenside expansion by eventually playing b4 , being careful not to lock down the position. } 
6. Nc3 Nf6 
7. Bd3 {[%cal Bc4c5,Bd3b5,Bf3g5,Bg5e6][%csl Bc5,Bb5,Be6]} { Black can play g6 to stabilize the f-pawn, but must avoid trading light square bishops at all costs to prevent losing control over e6. The move f4 invites c5, undermining the pawn chain and preparing Bb5+ in an effort to trade bishops. } Bd7 { If Black had continued with f4 , White would immediately execute the c5 plan. If Black had tried to support the f5-pawn with g6 , White would continue with h2-h4-h5 . } 
8. exf5 { Despite the resource c5, White avoids castling in fear of the f4 advance. } Nxf5 
9. O-O {[%cal Bh2h3,Bg2g4,Bf3g5,Bg5e6,Bc4c5][%csl Be6,Bc5]} { White gets a sizeable +1.5 positional advantage, but converting it will take skill. Some immediate plans for White are the c5 advance and the strange looking h2-h3 g2-g4 advance, followed by Nf3-Ng5-Ne6 and the f-pawn catapult. Alternatively, White could have started with the innocent looking 9. h3 , preparing to immediately play g2-g4-g5 if Black plays the natural looking 10. Be7 . Anticipating the g-pawn advance, Black should instead continue with 10. g6 , providing the f6-knight with a safe square on h5 and preventing discovered attacks along the d1-h5 diagonal. } *

